	<header class="entry-header">
		<h1 class="entry-title">Nigh</h1>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>These pants are itching. Of course, these are the itchy pants. There is no time to go and change. I‚Äôm late anyway. Hey! This is a pedestrian crossing, you idiot. City full of idiots. It‚Äôs 8:08 and I‚Äôm still three blocks away. And it looks like it‚Äôs about to rain. The sky ‚Äì I look up. There‚Äôs something wrong with the ‚Äì</p>
<p>‚ÄúSir, we‚Äôve double checked. No, it‚Äôs not a tornado‚Äù, but they don‚Äôt listen. Jenny shakes her head. We‚Äôve run the data twice, called the lab in Newark, they get the same thing. ‚ÄúIt might be ‚Äì some sort of electrical storm?‚Äù Jenny shrugs. We have no clue, but nobody wants to hear that. ‚ÄúLook, just keep the emergency services ‚Äì‚Äú</p>
<p>I didn‚Äôt turn on the siren, but he knows I‚Äôm coming. The elevator is dead. Shit. This must be twenty stories. God, I wish I‚Äôd kept up the training. Jesus. The air feels thin, stretched. I pray it‚Äôs me, but damn it, it‚Äôs the bleeding inversion field, isn‚Äôt it? That‚Äôs how he said it would feel, just before ‚Äì </p>
<p>The sky stretches around me, metal grey. It feels ready, vibrating like a violin string about to break. The inversion is mounting. I have made a little display that measures all the time left in the world. Nineteen seconds now. It‚Äôs 8:08. I hear someone thundering up the stairs. He won‚Äôt make it. None of us will. I feel compelled to maniacal laughter, but there‚Äôs just not enough &#8211;  </p>
	</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	
