		<li id="comment-621" class="comment byuser comment-author-rudyneeser odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 parent">
			<article id="div-comment-621" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=56&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=112&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-56 photo avatar-default' height='56' width='56' />						<b class="fn"><a href='http://rudyneeser.wordpress.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Rudy Neeser</a></b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="http://localhost:8888/microfiction.co.za/2010/09/19/291/#comment-621">
							<time datetime="2010-09-24T08:06:32+00:00">
								September 24, 2010 at 8:06 am							</time>
						</a>
											</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>This is a series of snapshots of people who are involved in a city&#8217;s (the world&#8217;s?) destruction. The first character seems to be a pedestrian, the second is perhaps a climatologist ‚Äî definitely seems like a professional of some sort. The third is someone running up the stairs attempting to stop the device which causes the destruction. The fourth person seems to have set up the device, and seems to be waiting for the destruction of the world. </p>
<p>My first thought was: ha! Amusing South African name. I do enjoy how the name goes along with the story.</p>
<p>I enjoyed the voices. I thought that they all came across quite naturally. There were two spots where I thought things were a bit intrusive, which I point out below.</p>
<p>&gt; The sky ‚Äì I look up.<br />
The rest of the paragraph before this (and after it) was very much in the character&#8217;s mind ‚Äî having the character narrate that they&#8217;re looking up broke that for me.</p>
<p>&gt; I have made a little display that measures all the time left in the<br />
&gt; world.<br />
All of the characters were never exactly narrating to us ‚Äî they were thinking things and talking to each other, and we were getting to observe them. The Villain, however, decides to tell us that they&#8217;ve built this display. Felt out of place.</p>
<p>There are some other places where the characters come close to narrating, but they didn&#8217;t feel intrusive. </p>
<p>&gt; No, it‚Äôs not a tornado‚Äù,<br />
Comma should be thus: &#8220;&#8230;it&#8217;s not a tornado,&#8221;</p>
<p>I enjoyed this piece. The voices are great and the story fun.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

